# How helm works under the hood

[helm using secrets](https://codeengineered.com/blog/2020/helm-secret-storage/)
[helm secret details](https://gist.github.com/DzeryCZ/c4adf39d4a1a99ae6e594a183628eaee)


why secrets work:
- opaque -> use a structure
- encrypted storage
- core api -> crd has permission issues for installation
- no validation -> secrets are used and validated by helm alone

So in order to decode the data, you have to:
- base64 decode - Kubernetes secrets encoding
- base64 decode (again) - Helm encoding
- gzip decompress - Helm zipping

kubectl get secrets sh.helm.release.v1.mysql-1710723616.v1 -o json | jq .data.release | tr -d '"' | base64 -d | base64 -d | gzip -d

```
k get secrets mysql-1710723616 -o yaml
apiVersion: v1
data:
  mysql-password: WWxlVjM0UzZiUA==
  mysql-root-password: bW5YNDVLV1FJWg==
kind: Secret
metadata:
  annotations:
    meta.helm.sh/release-name: mysql-1710723616
    meta.helm.sh/release-namespace: default
  creationTimestamp: "2024-03-18T01:00:19Z"

    app.kubernetes.io/instance: mysql-1710723616
    app.kubernetes.io/managed-by: Helm

    helm.sh/chart: mysql-9.23.0

```


convention:
sh.helm.release.v1.[instance name].[release version]

```
k get secrets sh.helm.release.v1.mysql-1710723616.v1 -o yaml

  creationTimestamp: "2024-03-18T01:00:18Z"
  labels:
    modifiedAt: "1710723619"
```
